{
  "doc_id": "3153",
  "text": "Three decades after the discovery of HIV, the journey towards the development of a protective HIV vaccine is still ongoing. While the overarching goal of an HIV antibody-based vaccine is to induce broadly neutralizing antibodies, this historically has not proven to be an easy feat [CITATION_1] . To date, there have only been four different HIV vaccine concepts that have been tested in a total of six human efficacy trials [CITATION_2] . Of these, the RV144 'Thai' Phase III trial was the first, and only, human HIV vaccine trial to demonstrate moderate efficacy (31.2%) [CITATION_3] . Surprisingly, this vaccine did not induce broadly neutralizing antibody responses. Instead non-neutralizing antibodies that recognize a specific region of the HIV Envelope (ENV) variable region 1 and 2 (V1V2) were associated with reduced risk of infection [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Additional follow up analysis of the RV144 trial revealed that ADCC, antibody avidity to ENV and low tier neutralizing antibodies in the absence of IgA were secondary correlates of reduced risk of infection [CITATION_6] .",
